Lessons that can be learned today from the Cuban Missile Crisis
"Thirteen Days" ("Dreizehn Tage"), a new film about the Cuban Missile Crisis, will soon be released in cinemas in many countries.
Everyone should see this work, not only because the film deals with the past, but also because it offers insights into current events—particularly regarding the controversies surrounding a U.S. national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy called his closest advisors together in the White House.
Aerial photographs of the region had revealed the construction of a nuclear weapons station on Cuba.
The decisions made in the following thirteen days, and the decisions that could not be made, could have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened in the White House during those days.
Sound recordings made during Kennedy's presidency played a significant role in the production of the film.
After the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard organized a panel discussion to discuss the film as well as the crisis it addresses.
Participants in this panel included, among others: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a history professor at Harvard who wrote a book about the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a professor of political science at Harvard who presented a classic study on the Cuban Missile Crisis, the work "Essence of Decision," 30 years ago.
Moreover, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was also present.
Although the film's treatment of the subject was criticized in various respects, the discussion participants were able to agree that the film accurately portrays the problems and pressure President Kennedy faced.
What conclusions can be drawn from the Cuban Missile Crisis today?
Theodore Sorensen summarized them as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in the event of a crisis, but it is exclusively the President who ultimately bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – both civilian and military – wanted to attack Cuba at that time.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his probing questions could alternatives and dangers be presented that were essential in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how an adversary thinks; furthermore, communication channels must be kept open.
Pressing an adversary into a corner without keeping diplomatic channels open that allow for an understanding of the adversary's situation could prove disastrous.
· The United States relies on allies.
Kennedy acted in this way because the NATO alliance, additional allies, and world opinion had supported him.
· A certain period of time is necessary to make good decisions.
When it comes to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to urge him into taking an action.
The fact that a week passed in which all involved factors were examined and weighed with the greatest precision was decisive for the outcome.
Yet would such a period of time for deliberation even exist today in the face of the mass media that currently exist?
Robert McNamara has emphasized that it is necessary to put oneself in the adversary's position.
In one of the film's most criticized scenes, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade that Kennedy imposed on Cuba was primarily intended to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's intent, and was not meant as a means to stop certain Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted even more calmly?
After all, the United States had also stationed atomic warheads near the Soviet Union.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles in Cuba only reflected this policy.
Yet Kennedy was anxious about the consequences that the stationing of Soviet missiles in Cuba would have regarding Berlin.
The pressure of nuclear weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
Ultimately, "the Berlin crisis was resolved through the outcomes of the Cuban Missile Crisis," claimed historian Ernest May.
" Soon it will be too late," was a widely circulated argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba while the missiles — as they assumed — were en route to Cuba by sea.
An approximately 180,000-strong U.S. force was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a massive bombing campaign that would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. "It took me thirty years," said McNamara, "to find out that there had already been atomic weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, and 90 of them strategic nuclear warheads."
McNamara received this information on the occasion of a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He posed the following three questions to Castro: 1) Did you know about it?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro replied: "I knew about it."
And I explicitly recommended that nuclear weapons be used.
I knew that this would have led to the annihilation of Cuba."
Castro and—to a greater extent—his comrade Che Guevara were ready to let Cuba go up in smoke, so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for world revolution!
An invasion would thus have resulted in the death of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because the Kennedy administration lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (a situation that often occurs when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is firmly convinced that an invasion "undoubtedly" would have led to a Soviet atomic attack against the United States.
Khrushchev's control over the Soviet military in Cuba was indeed limited: U-2 aircraft flying over Cuban airspace were shot down despite explicit orders to the contrary from the chairman.
A difficult question to answer, which did not come up during this debate at Harvard, is the following: What would have happened if the adversary had not been Khrushchev, who distinguished himself during the crisis by more rational behavior, but rather an opponent of the type of Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
Given the spread of nuclear weapons, this danger could one day become reality.
Today's discussions about limited missile defense and the threat of nuclear blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in the light of this terrible but quite realistic thought.
Harvard has launched a new website on the Internet where essential documents about the Cuban Missile Crisis and current nuclear threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org.
